message.content: One of the most significant events that happened in Thailand in the past 100 years is the Siamese Revolution of 1932. This event marked the transition of Thailand from an absolute monarchy to a constitutional monarchy. On June 24, 1932, a group of military and civilian officials, known as the People's Party, staged a bloodless coup and demanded political reforms. As a result, King Prajadhipok (Rama VII) was forced to grant a constitution, establishing a constitutional monarchy and ending centuries of absolute rule by the monarchy. This event had a profound impact on Thai politics and society, shaping the country's political landscape for years to come.
